{{short description|A nanocrystalline form of diamond}} {{redirect|hyperdiamond|4-polytope|24-cell}} [[File:Popigai nanodiamonds.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Natural nanodiamond aggregates from the [[Popigai crater]], Siberia, Russia.<ref name=popigai>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/srep14702|pmid=26424384|pmc=4589680|title=Natural occurrence of pure nano-polycrystalline diamond from impact crater|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=5|pages=14702|year=2015|last1=Ohfuji|first1=Hiroaki|last2=Irifune|first2=Tetsuo|last3=Litasov|first3=Konstantin D.|last4=Yamashita|first4=Tomoharu|last5=Isobe|first5=Futoshi|last6=Afanasiev|first6=Valentin P.|last7=Pokhilenko|first7=Nikolai P.|bibcode = 2015NatSR...514702O }}</ref>]] [[File:Natural nanodiamond TEM.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Internal structure of the Popigai nanodiamonds.<ref name=popigai/>]] [[File:Synthetic nanodiamond TEM.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Internal structure of synthetic nanodiamonds.<ref name=popigai/>]] '''Aggregated diamond nanorods''', or '''ADNRs''', are a [[nanocrystalline]] form of [[diamond]], also known as '''nanodiamond''' or '''hyperdiamond'''.
== Discovery ==
Nanodiamond or hyperdiamond was convincingly demonstrated to be produced by compression of [[graphite]] in 2003 and in the same work found to be much harder than bulk diamond.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Irifune |first1=Tetsuo |last2=Kurio |first2=Ayako |last3=Sakamoto |first3=Shizue|last4=Inoue |first4=Toru |last5=Sumiya |first5=Hitoshi |title=Materials: Ultrahard polycrystalline diamond from graphite |journal=Nature |volume=421 |pages=599–600 |year=2003 |doi=10.1038/421599b |pmid=12571587 |issue=6923|bibcode = 2003Natur.421..599I }}</ref> Later it was also produced by compression of [[fullerene]] and confirmed to be the hardest and least compressible known material, with an [[isothermal bulk modulus]] of 491 [[pascal (unit)|gigapascals]] (GPa), while a conventional diamond has a modulus of 442–446 GPa; these results were inferred from [[X-ray diffraction]] data, which also indicated that ADNRs are 0.3% denser than regular diamond.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dubrovinskaia |first1=Natalia |last2=Dubrovinsky |first2=Leonid |last3=Crichton |first3=Wilson |last4=Langenhorst |first4=Falko |last5=Richter |first5=Asta |title=Aggregated diamond nanorods, the densest and least compressible form of carbon |journal=Applied Physics Letters |volume=87 |issue=8 |pages=083106 |year=2005 |doi=10.1063/1.2034101 |bibcode=2005ApPhL..87h3106D}}</ref> The same group later described ADNRs as "having a hardness and [[Young's modulus]] comparable to that of natural diamond, but with 'superior wear resistance'".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dubrovinskaia |first1=Natalia |last2=Dub |first2=Sergey |last3=Dubrovinsky |first3=Leonid |title=Superior Wear Resistance of Aggregated Diamond Nanorods |journal=Nano Letters |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=824 |year=2006 |doi=10.1021/nl0602084|pmid=16608291 |bibcode = 2006NanoL...6..824D }}</ref>
== Hardness == A [[Miller index|&lt;111&gt;]] surface (normal to the largest diagonal of a cube) of pure diamond has a hardness value of 167±6 GPa when scratched with a nanodiamond tip, while the nanodiamond sample itself has a value of 310 GPa when tested with a nanodiamond tip.<ref name=blank>{{cite journal|last1=Blank |first1=V |title=Ultrahard and superhard phases of fullerite C<sub>60</sub>: Comparison with diamond on hardness and wear |url=http://nanoscan.info/wp-content/publications/article_03.pdf |journal=Diamond and Related Materials |volume=7 |issue=2–5 |pages=427 |year=1998 |doi=10.1016/S0925-9635(97)00232-X |bibcode=1998DRM.....7..427B |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721225258/http://nanoscan.info/wp-content/publications/article_03.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-21 |df= }}</ref> However, the test only works properly with a tip made of harder material than the sample being tested. This means that the true value for nanodiamond is likely somewhat lower than 310 GPa.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}
== Synthesis == ADNRs (hyper diamonds / nano diamonds) are produced by compressing fullerite powder—a solid form of [[allotropy|allotropic]] carbon fullerene—by any of two somewhat similar methods. One uses a [[diamond anvil cell]] and applied pressure ~37 GPa without heating the cell.<ref name=blank2>{{cite journal |last1=Blank |first1=V |last2=Popov |first2=M |last3=Buga |first3=S |last4=Davydov |first4=V |last5=Denisov |first5=V |last6=Ivlev |first6=A |last7=Marvin |first7=B |last8=Agafonov |first8=V |last9=Ceolin |first9=R |displayauthors=8|title=Is C<sub>60</sub> fullerite harder than diamond? |journal=Physics Letters A |volume=188 |issue=3 |pages=281 |year=1994 |doi=10.1016/0375-9601(94)90451-0|bibcode = 1994PhLA..188..281B }}</ref> In another method, fullerite is compressed to lower pressures (2–20 GPa) and then heated to a temperature in the range of {{convert|300|to|2500|K|C}}.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kozlov |first1=M |title=Superhard form of carbon obtained from C<sub>60</sub> at moderate pressure |journal=Synthetic Metals |volume=70 |pages=1411 |year=1995 |doi=10.1016/0379-6779(94)02900-J}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Blank |first1=V |title=Ultrahard and superhard carbon phases produced from C<sub>60</sub> by heating at high pressure: structural and Raman studies |journal=Physics Letters A |volume=205 |issue=2–3 |pages=208 |year=1995|doi=10.1016/0375-9601(95)00564-J|bibcode = 1995PhLA..205..208B }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Szwarc |first1=H |last2=Davydov |first2=V |last3=Plotianskaya |first3=S |last4=Kashevarova |first4=L |last5=Agafonov |first5=V |last6=Ceolin |first6=R |title=Chemical modifications of C under the influence of pressure and temperature: from cubic C to diamond |journal=Synthetic Metals |volume=77 |pages=265 |year=1996 |doi=10.1016/0379-6779(96)80100-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Blank |first1=V |title=Phase transformations in solid C<sub>60</sub> at high-pressure-high-temperature treatment and the structure of 3D polymerized fullerites |journal=Physics Letters A |volume=220 |pages=149 |year=1996 |doi=10.1016/0375-9601(96)00483-5|bibcode = 1996PhLA..220..149B }}</ref> Extreme hardness of what now appears likely to have been nanodiamonds was reported by researchers in the 1990s.<ref name=blank/><ref name=blank2/> The material is a series of interconnected diamond nanorods, with diameters of between 5 and 20 [[nanometre]]s and lengths of around 1 [[micrometre]] each.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}
Nanodiamond aggregates ca. 1 mm in size also form in nature, from graphite upon meteoritic impact, such as that of the [[Popigai crater]] in Siberia, Russia.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/srep14702|pmid=26424384|pmc=4589680|title=Natural occurrence of pure nano-polycrystalline diamond from impact crater|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=5|pages=14702|year=2015|last1=Ohfuji|first1=Hiroaki|last2=Irifune|first2=Tetsuo|last3=Litasov|first3=Konstantin D.|last4=Yamashita|first4=Tomoharu|last5=Isobe|first5=Futoshi|last6=Afanasiev|first6=Valentin P.|last7=Pokhilenko|first7=Nikolai P.|bibcode = 2015NatSR...514702O }}</ref>
